'''Furryville''' is a [[Germany|German]] line of [[Mattel]] toys that launched in 2005. <ref>[http://service.mattel.com/us/productPopup.aspx?prodno=H2300&siteid=27 Furryville™ Bunningtons™ in the Garden], Mattel.com.</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://toyfair05.alteredstatesmag.com/companies/mattel-press-kit/tf05-mattel-press-furryville/ | title = Toy Fair 2005 - Mattel Furryville Press Kit | accessdate=2008-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mattel.de/press.php?rid=1129542450&action=show&f=y | title = Mattel press release (German) | accessdate=2008-05-14}}</ref> Furryville toys are small [[stuffed animal]]s up to 3 inches in height. The line consists of many types of animals, usually sold in sets. They are typically packaged as either a family of four animals of the same species or as "two-furs", two toys sold together (but not always of the same species). A Furryville toy can also be sold individually, such as "Kangaroo Court" (a tennis-playing kangaroo) or "Sensational Groom" (a wedding skunk). They are available online only.
The families are named for their species, in additions to groups like "Family Moments", "Around the World" and "Town Collection".
In 2006, Mattel came under fire from nurses for a new single called "Nurse Quacktitioner". Thousands of nurses complained to Mattel about the reference to "quacks" -- [[Quackery|in medicine]] a common expression for a medical practitioner who is a fraud. Mattel replied that the figure was a duck, and that ducks "quack".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.truthaboutnursing.org/news/2006/jan/11_mattel.html |title=Mattel on the "Nurse Quacktitioner": Problem? What problem? Oh--and did we mention the new Nurse Barbie? |date=11 January 2006 |publisher=The Truth About Nursing |accessdate=11 June 2013}}</ref> The figure was withdrawn from the market.
